  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Health Emergency Response in drought affected areas ensuring life-saving trauma care services and improved capacities for outbreak response including CCHF</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project will respond to the current humanitarian emergency in Western and Southern regions of Afghanistan as identified under the priority by the Humanitarian Country Team. A combination of prolonged conflict and acute environmental crisis of drought has strained the ability of existing public health services to beyond capacity, critically endangering the lives of the population.  While this current drought has placed a significant burden on the current health system, the project will address element of the Health Cluster response including: 1) disease outbreaks 2) trauma care 3) prepositioning of essential supply as part of a preparedness plan for the ongoing drought response .

The  ongoing conflicts and recurrent natural disasters expose the affected population of Afghanistan to high risks of public health outbreaks, the emerging and re-emerging epidemic diseases pose an ongoing threat to global health security, Currently, Afghanistan is recording the highest number of cases of Crimean Congo Hemorrhagic Fever in the past 14 years with outbreaks in the same geographic regions as drought. CCHF is a highly fatal viral zoonotic disease with case fatality ratio up to 40% (WHO, 2013).  The number of CCHF cases (347) shows significant increase (225% increase).  Cases have been reported in 29 out of 34 provinces with Kabul and Herat reported the highest numbers. The number of CCHF patients hospitalized  in Infectious Disease Hospital  during first week of September, 20132018 reached to 35 while the available beds were only 10.

In addition, this project will support urgent trauma care in Helmand province as one of priority objective under the Health Cluster.  The EMERGENCY Surgical Centre for war victims in Lashkargah is facing new challenges due to the worsening of the conflict, increase in mass casualties and severity of the injuries. The number of severe injuries has increased: average of operations per patient increase 9% (in 2017 is 2,3 operations per patient), average of length of stay per patient increased 22% (6,9% in 2017), major surgeries as amputation increased 19% compare to 2016.

This project will cover three priorities:
1)      Capacity building and scale up surveillance of CCHF in drought-affected districts
2)      Scale up trauma care in Lashkargah Emergency hospital to improve trauma care
3)      Procurement of essential medical supply to support emergency health services in drought affected population.</narrative>
  </description>
